{
  "answer": "Fichte argues that *Denkfreiheit*—literally, the freedom of *thinking* as an ongoing, self-directed activity constitutive of human personhood—is inalienable because it is the active exercise of reason against passive, mechanical association of ideas (as in animals). Rendering it as \"freedom of thought\" in English risks nominalizing *Denken* (thinking) into a static object or content (like beliefs or opinions), thereby obscuring its dynamic essence as free self-activity: the power to \"give a definite direction to one's own sequence of ideas by one's own power, according to one's own free will.\"[^1] This activity is not merely permitted (and thus alienable via social contract) but demanded by reason's drive \"into the infinite,\" making any restriction a violation of personhood itself.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, ch. 2 [paragraph](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-e62dae).\n\n[^2]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, ch. 2 [paragraph](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-19e488).",
